but in this particular problem, we have the following potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V=-Fx$
\end_inset

, then the Lagrangian becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=\frac{m}{2}\dot{x}^{2}+Fx,
\]

\end_inset

and then, the derivatives are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{x}}=m\dot{x},\implies\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{x}}=m\ddot{x},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial L}{\partial x}=F,
\]

\end_inset

then the Euler-Lagrange equation becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F-m\ddot{x}=0\iff\ddot{x}=\frac{F}{m},
\]

\end_inset

then we can integrate the previous equation with respect to time, such that
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int\frac{d\dot{x}}{dt}dt=\frac{F}{m}\int dt,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\dot{x}=\frac{F}{m}t+\alpha,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 its just an integration constant, and performing another integration, we
 have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int\frac{dx}{dt}dt=\frac{F}{m}\int tdt+\alpha\int dt,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies x=\frac{F}{2m}t^{2}+\alpha t+\beta,
