\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Solution.
 
\series default
Let's begin by writting the Lagrangian
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=\exp\left(\gamma t\right)\left(\frac{m}{2}\dot{q}^{2}-\frac{k}{2}q^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset

which is known as the Batemas's Lagrangian.
 We know that the Lagrange Equations are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial L}{\partial q}-\frac{d}{dt}\left(\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{q}}\right)=0,
\]

\end_inset

so, let's calculate the derivates 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{q}}=m\dot{q}\exp\left(\gamma t\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{q}}=m\ddot{q}\exp\left(\gamma t\right)+m\gamma\dot{q}\exp\left(\gamma t\right)=\left(m\ddot{q}+m\gamma\dot{q}\right)\exp\left(\gamma t\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore\frac{d}{dt}\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{q}}=\left(m\ddot{q}+m\gamma\dot{q}\right)\exp\left(\gamma t\right),
\]

\end_inset

on the other hand 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial L}{\partial q}=-kq\exp\left(\gamma t\right),
\]

\end_inset

then, we have that the Euler-Lagrange equations is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-kq\exp\left(\gamma t\right)-\left(m\ddot{q}+m\gamma\dot{q}\right)\exp\left(\gamma t\right)=0,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iff m\left(\ddot{q}+\frac{\gamma}{m}\dot{q}+\frac{k}{m}q\right)\exp\left(\gamma t\right)=0,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iff\left(\ddot{q}+\alpha\dot{q}+\beta q\right)=0,
\]

\end_inset

ehere 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\gamma/m$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=k/m$
\end_inset

, but the previous equation it's just the equation of motion for a damped
 oscillator.
 On the other hand, if we make the following point transformation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s=\exp\left(\gamma t/2\right)q,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies q=\exp\left(-\gamma t/2\right)s,
\]

\end_inset

then we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{s}=\gamma\exp\left(\gamma t/2\right)q+\exp\left(\gamma t/2\right)\dot{q}=\gamma\exp\left(\gamma t/2\right)\left(\exp\left(-\gamma t/2\right)s\right)+\exp\left(\gamma t/2\right)\dot{q},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\dot{s}=\gamma s+\exp\left(\gamma t/2\right)\dot{q},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\dot{q}=\left(\dot{s}-\gamma s\right)\exp\left(-\gamma t/2\right),
\]

\end_inset

therefore, if we substitute the previous results in the original Lagrangian,
 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=\exp\left(\gamma t\right)\left(\frac{m}{2}\left(\left(\dot{s}-\gamma s\right)\exp\left(-\gamma t/2\right)\right)^{2}-\frac{k}{2}\left(\exp\left(-\gamma t/2\right)s\right)^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies L=\exp\left(\gamma t\right)\left(\frac{m}{2}\exp\left(-\gamma t\right)\left(\dot{s}-\gamma s\right)^{2}-\frac{k}{2}\exp\left(-\gamma t\right)s^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore L=\frac{m}{2}\left(\dot{s}-\gamma s\right)^{2}-\frac{k}{2}s^{2},
\]

\end_inset

therefore, with that transformation we can get rid of the explicit time
 dependence in the Lagrangian.
\end_layout

